  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Okay, here&#39;s a new, heavily revised version of my first deck. Definitely some significant changes here. I managed to shave off 24 cards, so the deck is definitely more focused (not to mention easier to shuffle, eh?). Some of the more noticible changes I&#39;ve made include adding Gandalf (cause he&#39;s tough), cutting waaaaaay back on most of the aversion events in the Free Peoples half of the deck, and losing the Cave Trolls (what the hell was I thinking?! Can&#39;t even play them in this deck). <br />
<br />
I&#39;ve noticed a trend here (Utah -- blah!) of people bidding zero for the right to go first, so I wouldn&#39;t bid more than 2. There are, of course, 4 Aragorns in the deck, so it&#39;s not that big of a loss if I don&#39;t go first. Nazgul are also huge here, so I&#39;d stop moving if there&#39;s more than one minion left (unless they&#39;re all exhausted, of course). Now there is a finite number of ways to play this game, especially with a deck like this. Generally, you want to move, take archery shots, pump up your characters, and work your way through minions, while at the same time tossing down Nazgul to provide the opponent with opposition. Sounds simple, huh?<br />
<br />
Here are a few reasons for specific card choices:<br />
*Athelas: I cringe when I see decks with less than 4 of these. Blade Tip and Black Breath are too nasty to only play with 2 or 3 Athelas.<br />
*Double Shot: It plays for free, and it&#39;s another wound your opponent has to deal with. It also helps get around any &#39;archery -1&#39; stunts your opponent might pull.<br />
*Black Breath & Blade Tip: I wish I could play more than 4 each of these. They&#39;re sooooooo good.<br />
*Dagger Strike: I know it&#39;s useful in a Hobbit deck, but it also works with Aragorn when he&#39;s got his sword. <br />
*Tale Of Gil-galad: It gives Legolas an extra chance to wound someone, or burn it to make him tougher. Sounds good to me.<br />
*Gwemegil: I don&#39;t know why this is in here. It almost always gets discarded from Arwen. I guess it&#39;s in here for the off chance it might be useful sometime.<br />
*Ulaire Lemenya: Ideally, I&#39;d like to have 3 of him in the deck. With all the Blade Tips and Black Breaths floating around, he&#39;s pretty neat. <br />
<br />
That aboot sums it up, folks. Pretty stright forward deck, I guess. Now my aim here is to get CONSTRUCTIVE FEEDBACK on this deck. I don&#39;t care if you think the deck rocks or the deck sucks, so long as you tell my why.  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
